{"key":"processedPost-19521948","value":{"id":19521948,"first":19521544,"last":19522057,"when":1391566467,"utime":"02/05/14 04:14 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />for my second flush, am I able to lay the cakes on their side so that this issue of falling cakes doesn't persist?<br /></blockquote><br /><br />They'll just roll over instead. <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/laugh.gif\" alt=\":laugh:\" title=\":laugh:\"/><br /><br />I experimented with a few dozen shiitake blocks several years ago, by colonizing them one way and fruiting them upside down.&nbsp; Performance was almost always crappy compared to fruiting them in the same orientation they colonized in.&nbsp; I duplicated the experiment by fruiting them right side up for first flush and upside down for second.&nbsp; Performance was again less than leaving them upright from colonization through final flush.<br /><br />Whether this correlates to cubes or not I have no idea.&nbsp; On the left are shiitake blocks fruited the same orientation as they colonized.&nbsp; On the right are blocks of the same isolated strain turned upside down.&nbsp; Note that almost no mushrooms formed on what was the bottom of the substrate during colonization.<br />RR<br /><br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/10-51/306045132-Shiitake_720_024a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/10-51/306045132-thumb_Shiitake_720_024a.jpg\"></a>&nbsp; <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/10-51/287361564-Shiitake_720_003a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/10-51/287361564-thumb_Shiitake_720_003a.jpg\"></a>","title":"Re: Lay my BRF baby down...."}}